title.narrative: SAM TREATMENT

description.narrative: By December 2018, Ministry of Health and Sanitation (MoHS) has improved capacity to provide equitable and quality integrated management of severe acute malnutrition services to children under the age of five in all districts with focus in hard to reach communities, which contributes to Community-Based Management Of Acute Malnutrition, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Improved and equitable use of nutritional and care services by communities with a special focus on nutritionally-at-risk children and women residing in the hard to reach areas by end of December 2018

title.narrative: By December 2018, Ministry of Health and Sanitation (MoHS) has improved capacity to provide equitable and quality integratedmanagement of severe acute malnutrition services to children under the age of five in all districts with focus in hard to reachcommunities

description.narrative: With over 95 percent cure rate at national level, treatment outcome of the Integrated Management of Acute Malnutrition (IMAM) programme met the global SPHERE standards for cure, default and death rates, demonstrating increased capacity to provide equitable and quality treatment for Severe Acute Malnutrition (SAM). Improved access to community nutrition services contributed to high admission rate (84 percent) against the estimated annual caseload in seven UNICEF-targeted districts. The identification and addressing of bottlenecks contributed to better performance of IMAM sites in UNICEF-targeted districts with 75 percent of outpatient sites meeting SPHERE standard for cure rate compared to 26 percent elsewhere. | Status:Met | As-of Date:05/02/2020
